  "prompt": "How can you determine the ionic charge of sodium?",
  "response": "To determine the ionic charge of sodium, you need to understand its position on the periodic table and its electron configuration. Sodium (Na) is an alkali metal located in Group 1 of the periodic table. Elements in this group have a single electron in their outermost shell.\n\nThe electron configuration of a neutral sodium atom is \\(1s^2 2s^2 2p^6 3s^1\\). Sodium prefers to achieve a stable electron configuration similar to the nearest noble gas, which is neon in this case, by losing its one valence electron in the 3s orbital. When sodium loses this electron, it achieves a full outer shell, resulting in a more stable, positively charged ion: Na\u207a.\n\nThus, the ionic charge of sodium is +1.",
